            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Chloe Donovan\u2019s sense of civic duty was baked into her upbringing in San Francisco\u2019s Sunset District. The daughter of a pragmatic Chinese-American mother and an idealistic Irish-American father, Chloe grew up behind the counter of their family-run cafe, a neighborhood hub where conversations about city politics were as common as orders for coffee. She witnessed firsthand how municipal decisions\u2014zoning changes, new bus lines, small business grants\u2014directly impacted the lives and livelihoods of her neighbors.\n\nThe key turning point came when she was sixteen. A city-led development project threatened to displace several local businesses, including her parents' cafe. Chloe watched them navigate a labyrinth of permits, public hearings, and bureaucratic red tape. The feeling of helplessness she saw in her community ignited a fire in her. She realized that understanding the system was the only way to change it for the better.\n\nThis experience became her North Star. She threw herself into her studies, earning a scholarship to UC Berkeley for her undergraduate degree and then a Master's in Public Policy. She focused her thesis on creating equitable urban development policies. Upon graduating, she landed a highly competitive role as a Legislative Aide at City Hall, working for a Supervisor who represented neighborhoods like her own.\n\nNow, Chloe lives in a small but bright apartment in Hayes Valley, a 1.7-mile MUNI ride from the office. Her days are a whirlwind of policy briefings, constituent emails, and the slow, grinding work of incremental change. Her $92,000 salary feels both substantial and limiting in a city this expensive, requiring careful budgeting. Her social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of friends, mostly fellow policy wonks, with whom she debates housing policy over ramen in Japantown or craft beer in the Mission.\n\nChloe\u2019s connection to San Francisco is etched into her purpose. She isn't just a resident; she sees herself as a steward. She dreams of one day moving from aide to author, drafting the very legislation that could have saved her parents and their friends years of struggle, ensuring that the city\u2019s growth benefits everyone, not just the powerful."
        },
